caption.text:
Photos by @_victoriarazo | Originally from Port-au-Prince, Haiti, the Dorjean-Desmornes family is among the tens of thousands of Haitians who fled to South America in search of work in the years following the devastating 2010 earthquake.

Rose Desmornes, 26, and Jeankely Dorjean, 35, eventually made their way north to Tijuana, Mexico, where they obtained legal residency and began to build a life. But Dorjean’s brother promised them good jobs in the U.S., so they left—just days before their second child was born. Now they're in the U.S., starting over again—huddled in a barren bedroom, depending on the generosity of family and friends for their daily needs. 
Their son was born in West Palm Beach, Florida. After only a few days there, they continued north, settling in New Jersey, a state with one of the highest numbers of Haitian migrants in the country.

caption.text:
Photo by @amivitale | An orphaned baby reticulated giraffe embraces @r.e.s.c.u.e wildlife keeper Lekupania. This giraffe, like others before him, will be rehabilitated and returned to the wild. Giraffes are undergoing what has been referred to as a silent extinction. Their populations across Africa are estimated to have dropped 40 percent in three decades, plummeting from approximately 155,000 in the late 1980s to under 100,000 today. 

The decline is thought to be caused by habitat loss, fragmentation, and poaching, but because there haven't been long-term conservation steps in the past, it's hard to know exactly what is happening. Reticulated giraffes number fewer than 16,000 individuals. Scientists are undertaking major studies to understand why giraffes are disappearing and what can be done to stop it. Follow @amivitale to learn more. 

#giraffes #giraffe #kenya

caption.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto | In April 2018 I joined a team of scientists working in Borneo's Gunung Mulu National Park. The team, led by Nele Meckler from the University of Bergen, is working to improve our understanding of tropical climate change over the last 500,000 years. In Deer Cave, one of the most impressive in the world, Gina Moseley from the University of Innsbruck is dwarfed by its overwhelming scale. Ever since I first walked into this cave in 2003, I've been in awe of this natural wonder.

media_or_ad.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic on February 20, 2022. May be an image of child, standing and outdoors.

caption.text: Photo by @williamodaniels | Rohingya refugees collect water in the Kutupalong refugee camp, in 2017. The Rohingya are a Muslim minority originally from the Rakhine state in Myanmar (Burma), where the population is mostly Buddhist. Since October 2015, nearly 712,000 have been displaced, according to UNHCR, crowding into refugee camps near Cox’s Bazar, just over the border in southern Bangladesh. They fled escalating violence from the Burmese army, denounced by the United Nations as ethnic cleansing. Following a 1982 law that forced them to prove their presence in the land before the British colonization in order to obtain nationality, they became stateless. Many have fled the country in successive waves for 40 years to reach their Muslim neighbor. The main refugee camp, Kutupalong, has grown to be the largest in the world, accommodating more than half a million people. Follow me on @williamodaniels for more stories.
